observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management: Instruct the MAO and GSO to exert best efforts to address the recurring audit observations (a), (c) and (e) through the conduct of one-time cleansing of PPE Account as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006, specifically:

Creation of Inventory Committee, whose members are temporarily relieved from their regular duties, to complete the conduct of inventory;

Disposal/ derecognition of non-existing/ missing PPE items.

Direct the GSO and the MAO to maintain and regularly update the Property Cards, Subsidiary Ledgers, PPE Ledger Cards, and other records in conformity with the MNGAS for LGUs;

Stop providing depreciation charges for unserviceable properties and facilitate their disposal in accordance with Section 79 of PD No. 1445; and

Thereafter, create an adjusting entry to adjust the PPE account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:

The Inventory Committee to undertake the physical count of inventory items as of June 30 and December 31 of each year; to prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) by inventory account name and distribute the same as prescribed;  to reconcile said report with the records of the Municipal Accounting Office in accordance with Section 124, Volume I of MNGAS; and to submit to the Office of the Auditor the duplicate copy of the RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;

Municipal Accountant to use moving average method as costing method for valuation of inventories as prescribed under Section 115, Chapter 7, Volume I of the MNGAS for LGUs;

MGSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards and regularly reconcile records to detect discrepancies and effect immediate corrections; and for the GSO to promptly prepare and submit the monthly SSMIs to the Municipal Accountant for recording in compliance with Sections 119 and 120, Volume I, of the MNGAS for LGUs; and

Strictly enjoin compliance with the above-cited rules for the fair presentation of inventory and related expense accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) and Investment Property, including a reconciliation of the physical count with the property and accounting records, as required by Chapter 4 of the Handbook on Property and Supply Management System and Paragraph 4 of Section 114 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I. Any discrepancies should be thoroughly investigated, cleared, immediately reconciled, and supported with written explanations from accountable persons, if necessary.
The procedures on one-time cleansing of PPE account balances are recommended per COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal General Services Office to enhance further their documentation and record-keeping practices related to PPE and Investment Property by preparing and continuously maintaining and updating PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively. Both offices should ensure that all movements of PPE are properly recorded and documented to facilitate accurate reconciliation and reporting;
The Disposal Committee to facilitate immediate disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with COA and Department of Budget and Management (DBM) Joint Circular No. 2024-1 or the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties; and
Relevant members of the Inventory Committee and Disposal Committee to undergo training on proper inventory procedures, reconciliation processes and record-keeping practices, as well as disposal procedures, including appraisal, documentation, and methods of disposal, if necessary.

We recommended that Management require:
The creation of an inventory committee consisting of representatives from different concerned offices to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality, which will prepare the necessary Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System (RPCRNS) using the form in Annex C of COA Circular 2015-008. The RPCRNS should be reconciled with the Accounting and GSO records;
The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and segregation of road components for those with data on construction costs. For those not posted in the registry but without identified cost and those included in the RPCRNS but not in the registry, the fair value must be used in determining the cost of road components and thereafter shall provide the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
The Municipal Accountant to depreciate the carrying amount of existing roads and its components to reflect the asset in its used condition and accordingly adjust the amount recorded in the Road Network account supported by the RPCRNS, Registry Infrastructure for Roads and working paper on the determination of the depreciated replacement cost per registry. Subsequently, at the end of each year, a lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation for each depreciable road component must be prepared as the basis for recording depreciation expenses and the required Local Road Network Ledger Card for each road network shall likewise be maintained; and
The Municipal General Services Office at the end of every accounting period to render a Report on Local Road Network using the pro-forma schedule in Annex A of the same Circular and maintain local road inventory, Road Map, and complete Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components.

To ensure fair presentation of the financial statements and compliance with accounting standards and regulations, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Conduct a thorough reconciliation of the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds accounts to determine the cause of the discrepancy and make necessary adjustments to ensure that both accounts are properly recognized;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the account balances;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers as necessary and include disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements for transparency; and
Strengthen internal controls and monitoring mechanisms to prevent future discrepancies in reciprocal accounts.

We recommended that Management:
a.	Reclassify the misrecorded balances from Accounts Payable to Due to Officers and Employees (2-01-01-020);
b.	Examine the payables to confirm and establish valid claims and submit to the Audit Team pertinent documents to support their validity; otherwise, effect deletion of those accounts which have no valid claims;
c.	Conduct a thorough review of all liability accounts to ensure they meet the criteria for recognition as per the provisions of IPSAS No. 1, namely: a) existence of a present obligation from past events, b) probability of outflow of resources embodying economic benefits, and c) reliable measurement of the obligation's cost/value; and
d.	Ensure that all obligations are supported by valid claims, bills, relevant records, and valid proofs to warrant payment. This includes maintaining subsidiary ledgers for each creditor with adequate information to justify the existence of such obligations.

We recommended that Management:
Assess the balances from completed projects and determine how the remaining funds can be lawfully and purposefully utilized for other priority projects;
Ensure alignment with the Memoranda of Agreement (MOAs) and funding terms governing the use of SNAP's financial assistance;
Regularly monitor project implementation and fund utilization to ensure timely actions are taken with regard to project completion and fund disposition; and
Formulate a plan for the utilization of idle funds to support continuing development programs and deliver tangible benefits to the constituents.

We recommended that Management:
Maintain ongoing compliance with COA Circular No. 94-013 in the proper grant, utilization and liquidation of the fund transfers from NGAs;
Ensure strict adherence to the guidelines specified in the respective Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) of each project while considering the principles outlined in P.D. 1445 regarding the management and utilization of government resources;
Advise the Municipal Accounting Office to reclassify the amount of ₱33,108.46 from the Due to NGA account to the Trust Liabilities account; and
Review and analyze the unsupported balances totaling ₱166,741.96 for proper disposition and ensure that all transactions are supported by complete and verifiable documentation.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Conduct a comprehensive review of the affected Repairs and Maintenance, PPE, Depreciation Expense, and Accumulated Depreciation accounts to ensure that all transactions are properly recognized and recorded in accordance with IPSAS 17;
Reclassify capitalizable repair and improvement costs from the Repairs and Maintenance account to the appropriate PPE accounts
Recognize the completed assets under their respective asset classifications once they are available for use;
Derecognize any replaced portions of PPE, if applicable, following the procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
Record the corresponding Depreciation Expense and Accumulated Depreciation starting from the date the asset became available for use.

We recommended that Management:
Develop and enforce an internal memorandum or directive requiring all concerned personnel to submit the Acceptance and Inspection Reports (AIRs) within 24 hours of goods acceptance;
Implement a tracking system for AIR submission;
Assign a focal person responsible for consolidating and submitting AIRs to the Office of the Auditor within the prescribed timeframe; and
If necessary, conduct a re-orientation for General Services Office personnel and end-users regarding proper documentation and timely submission of AIRs in accordance with COA Circulars.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to assure that the goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities are achieved;
Transfer to the Trust Liability-DRRMF account under Trust Fund the unexpended amount from savings in the implementation or non-implementation of Capital Outlay PPAs at the end of the year. To this end, the Accounting Office should conduct an analysis to determine all savings from implemented capital outlay PPAs from previous years to ensure their transfer to the Trust Liability-DRRMF account;
Ensure the allocation and utilization of LDRRMF according to the policies and guidelines primarily embodied in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1; and
Continuously comply with pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the recording, utilization and reporting of LDRRMF.

We recommended that the Municipality, in coordination with the Local School Board, being the one responsible for the formulation, approval, and utilization of the SEF Budget as provided under RA No. 7160 or the Local Government Code:
Sustain its efforts in ensuring that all budgeted projects, programs and activities are optimally and fully implemented within the target period and amount;
From time to time, revisit the revised guidelines on the use of SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 to ensure a more strategic and efficient formulation and utilization of resources for priority programs and projects;
Ensure that the allocation of the budget takes into account the priority areas specified under Section 100(c) of R.A. No. 7160 such as for sports development; and
For the purpose of hiring teachers chargeable against the SEF, the LSB in each province, city or municipality should utilize the list found in the Registry of Qualified Applicants (RQA).

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:
The Inventory Committee to undertake the physical count of inventory items as of June 30 and December 31 of each year; to prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) by inventory account name and distribute the same as prescribed;  to reconcile said report with the records of the Municipal Accounting Office in accordance with Section 124, Volume I of MNGAS; and to submit to the Office of the Auditor the duplicate copy of the RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Municipal Accountant to use moving average method as costing method for valuation of inventories as prescribed under Section 115, Chapter 7, Volume I of the MNGAS for LGUs;
MGSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards and regularly reconcile records to detect discrepancies and effect immediate corrections; and for the GSO to promptly prepare and submit the monthly SSMIs to the Municipal Accountant for recording in compliance with Sections 119 and 120, Volume I, of the MNGAS for LGUs; and
Strictly enjoin compliance with the above-cited rules for the fair presentation of inventory and related expense accounts in the financial statements.

We reiterated the following recommendations:
Direct the Municipality of Ramon Inventory and Disposal Committee to (i) conduct a complete physical count annually as required; (ii) intensify efforts to reconcile the result of physical count with property and accounting records and (iii) recommend for the adjustment of any noted discrepancy in compliance with Paragraph 2 of Section 124, Volume I of MNGAS for LGUs;
Direct the concerned Municipal Officials to maintain and regularly update property cards, subsidiary ledgers, property ledger cards, stock cards and other subsidiary records in conformity with Section 13, Volume II of the MNGAS for LGUs; and
Derecognize unserviceable properties from the books, stop providing depreciation charges for these assets and facilitate disposal of these properties in accordance with Section 79 of PD No. 1445;
Recognize the Road networks as carried in the Registry of Public Infrastructure in the books of accounts within the target set in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We reiterated the following recommendations:
Direct the Municipality of Ramon Inventory and Disposal Committee to (i) conduct a complete physical count annually as required; (ii) intensify efforts to reconcile the result of physical count with property and accounting records and (iii) recommend for the adjustment of any noted discrepancy in compliance with Paragraph 2 of Section 124, Volume I of MNGAS for LGUs;
Direct the concerned Municipal Officials to maintain and regularly update property cards, subsidiary ledgers, property ledger cards, stock cards and other subsidiary records in conformity with Section 13, Volume II of the MNGAS for LGUs;
Derecognize unserviceable properties in the books, stop providing depreciation charges for these assets and facilitate disposal of these properties in accordance with Section 79 of PD No. 1445; and
Recognize the Road networks as carried in the Registry of Public Infrastructure in the books of accounts within the target set in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that management consider the following:

Allocate the 20% development fund for projects that shall contribute to the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and shall partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures;
Utilize the fund to finance priority development projects and programs, as embodied in the duly approved Local Development plan and;
Instruct the Municipal Planning Development Officer, Budget Office and the Accountant to adhere strictly with the guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the 20% economic development fund prescribed under Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 of the DILG and DBM.

We recommended to the management the following:

Require that the gender issues and concerns prevailing among the women constituents be identified;
Map out the GAD projects/activities for the year and the corresponding specific strategies to address the issues;
Review and evaluate the results; and
The Accomplishment report should be prepared using the required form, to document the extent of implementation, the efficiency and effectiveness of the GAD projects and activities.
